THE SCENARIOS (Display one at a time)

Scenario 1: âYour manager asked for last monthâs sales figures. You have them ready in an Excel file.â

Scenario 2: âYour colleague made a factual error in a presentation that goes to the client in 30 minutes.â

Scenario 3: âYou need to give your teammate feedback that their recent work quality has declined.â

Scenario 4: âA client just emailed saying theyâre unhappy with your teamâs responsiveness.â

Scenario 5: âYou need to confirm tomorrowâs meeting time with 3 colleagues.â

Scenario 6: âYour vendor is 2 weeks late on a delivery. You need to escalate.â

Scenario 7: âYour manager just praised your work in front of the team. You want to thank them.â

Scenario 8: âYouâre resigning from your position.â

After showing all 10, facilitate discussion:

âWhat patterns did you notice?â

Capture answers on whiteboard. Guide toward these principles:

  1. Email when: You need a paper trail, sending attachments, explaining something complex, no urgency
  2. Slack/Chat when: Quick coordination, informal check-ins, team already using it actively
  3. Phone/Video when: Sensitive feedback, potential conflict, emotional de-escalation needed, urgent
  4. In-person when: Very sensitive topics (firing, resignation, serious feedback), building relationship

âWhatâs the biggest mistake you can make?â

(Expected answer: Giving negative feedback over email/text - it always goes badly)

Real example to share:

âLast year, a manager at an Indian startup laid off an employee via WhatsApp message. It went viral on Twitter. The companyâs reputation was damaged for months. The cost of choosing the wrong channel can be enormous.â

âA brief is a 1-page document designed to help someone make a decision quickly. Itâs not a report (which documents what happened) or a proposal (which sells an idea). Itâs pure decision support.

HANDOUT: The Messy Brief (distribute printed copies)

Subject: Thoughts on the CRM System Issue

Hi everyone,

I wanted to share some thoughts about our current CRM situation because I've been thinking about this quite a bit lately and there are several things we should probably consider.

As you all know, we've been using SalesTrack Pro for the past three years. It was fine when we started, but things have changed a lot since then. The company has grown, we have more customers now, and the sales team has expanded from 12 people to 35 people. This has created some challenges.

First of all, the system is really slow now. People are complaining that it takes forever to load customer records, especially in the morning when everyone is logging in at the same time. I've heard from multiple team members that they sometimes just keep customer information in Excel sheets because it's faster than waiting for SalesTrack to load. This is obviously not ideal because then we don't have a single source of truth.

Another issue is that SalesTrack doesn't integrate well with our new marketing automation platform (HubSpot) that we started using last quarter. The marketing team has to manually export lists and import them, which takes about 4-5 hours every week. There are often errors in this process, and sometimes leads fall through the cracks.

Also, the mobile app is pretty bad. Our field sales team needs to access customer information when they're traveling or at client sites, but the app crashes frequently and doesn't sync properly. Some of the senior salespeople have just stopped using it altogether.

I've been doing some research on alternative CRM systems. There are quite a few options out there - Salesforce, Zoho, Pipedrive, Freshworks, and some others. They all have different features and pricing models. Salesforce is the most popular but also the most expensive. Zoho is Indian-made and cheaper. Pipedrive is supposed to be very user-friendly. Freshworks has good reviews for customer support.

If we were to switch systems, we would need to migrate all our existing data, which could be complicated. We have about 15,000 customer records and 3 years of interaction history. We'd also need to train the sales team on the new system, which would take time and might disrupt their work temporarily.

The cost is also something to think about. SalesTrack costs us â¹8 lakhs per year. Some of the alternatives I looked at range from â¹6 lakhs to â¹18 lakhs annually depending on which features we want. There might also be one-time implementation costs.

On the other hand, if we don't do anything, the problems will probably get worse as we continue to grow. We're planning to hire 15 more salespeople next quarter, which will make the performance issues even more severe.

I think we should probably do something about this situation, but I'm not sure what the best approach is. Maybe we should form a committee to evaluate options? Or perhaps we should hire a consultant who specializes in CRM implementations?

Let me know what you all think.

Thanks,
Amit

SPEED WRITING DRILLS (45 minutes)

Facilitator Setup:

âNow weâre going to practice writing under real workplace pressure. In most jobs, you donât have hours to craft perfect emails. You have minutes. Weâre going to simulate that.â

DRILL 1: The Meeting Request (8 minutes writing + 5 min feedback)

Display scenario:

SITUATION:
You are Sneha Patel, Marketing Coordinator at FinTech Solutions India.

Your manager asked you to set up a meeting with Rajiv Malhotra, the Chief Digital Officer at a potential client company (IndusBank). Your manager wants to pitch IndusBank on your company's new digital banking platform.

CHALLENGE:
- You've never met Rajiv
- You only have his email (found on LinkedIn)
- He's very senior (C-suite) and presumably very busy
- You need a 45-minute meeting in the next 2 weeks
- Your manager wants you to handle this (not send it from her email)

TASK:
Write the email requesting this meeting. Make it compelling enough that he actually responds.

TIME LIMIT: 8 MINUTES. START NOW.

Students write in silence. Timer visible.

Peer Feedback Round (5 minutes)

Instructions:

âExchange with your neighbor. Read their email and answer: 1. Would a busy executive actually read this? 2. Is the value proposition clear? (Why should he meet with you?) 3. Is it easy to say yes? (Specific time options? Clear duration?)

Write 1-2 sentences of feedback at the bottom.â

Quick Debrief (2 minutes)

âWho got feedback that their email was too long? (hands up) Who was told their value proposition was unclear? (hands up)

Common mistake: We focus on US (âWeâre a leading fintech companyâ¦â) instead of THEM (âYour digital transformation roadmap needsâ¦â)â

DRILL 2: The Clarification Email (8 minutes writing + 5 min feedback)

Display scenario:

SITUATION:
You are Karan Desai, Junior Data Analyst.

This morning your manager sent you this Slack message:
"Karan - can you pull together that customer analysis we discussed and send it to the product team? They need it for planning."

PROBLEM:

1. Customer churn analysis (you finished this 2 weeks ago)
2. Customer segmentation by demographics (still in progress, 60% done)
3. Customer feedback sentiment analysis (hasn't been started yet)

You don't know:
- Which analysis she means
- When the product team needs it
- What level of detail they want (summary vs. full dataset)
- Who specifically on the product team should receive it

TASK:
Write an email asking for clarification WITHOUT sounding clueless or unprepared. Show that you've thought about this, you just need specific direction.

TIME LIMIT: 8 MINUTES. START NOW.

Peer Feedback Round (5 minutes)

Same process as Drill 1.

Quick Debrief (2 minutes)

âThis is one of the hardest emails to write. You need to: - Show youâre competent (not just saying âI donât understandâ) - Ask specific questions (not open-ended âWhat do you want?â) - Offer a plan pending her input (showing initiative)

DRILL 3: The Diplomatic Decline (10 minutes writing + 5 min feedback)

Display scenario:

SITUATION:
You are Pooja Reddy, Content Writer at a digital marketing agency.

Your colleague Arjun (from the design team) just Slacked you:
"Hey Pooja! Can you write social media captions for this campaign I'm working on? Client needs it by Friday. Probably like 15-20 posts? Thanks!!"

PROBLEM:
- You're already overloaded (working on 3 active client campaigns)
- This isn't your project (you weren't assigned to this client)
- Arjun didn't go through proper channels (should have asked your manager to assign you)
- He's underestimating the work (15-20 posts = 4-5 hours minimum)
- But Arjun is a nice person and you don't want to damage the relationship

TASK:
Decline this request professionally. Don't say yes (you genuinely cannot). Don't be rude (you work with Arjun regularly). Suggest an alternative solution if possible.

TIME LIMIT: 10 MINUTES. START NOW.

Peer Feedback Round (5 minutes)

Class Discussion (7 minutes)

Facilitator asks for 1-2 volunteers to read their responses aloud.

After each, discuss: - Did they say no clearly? - Did they maintain the relationship? - Did they suggest an alternative?

Model Response:

Hey Arjun!

I'd love to help, but I'm at capacity this week with three client campaigns (deadlines Thursday and Friday). I won't be able to deliver quality work on social captions by Friday.

Two suggestions:
1. Check with Priya (she mentioned having lighter load this week)
2. If timeline is flexible, I could potentially take this on next week

Teaching Point:

âThe art of saying no: 1. Say no clearly (donât hint, donât maybe) 2. Give a brief reason (but donât over-apologize) 3. Offer an alternative (show you care about the problem) 4. Maintain warmth (relationship matters)

âEverything youâve been practicing has names. Let me give you the labels:

âIf Iâd started Session 1 by saying âToday weâre learning the 7Cs,â you would have memorized them and forgotten them. Instead, you discovered WHY they matter by actually writing. The frameworks are just shortcuts to remember what you already learned through practice.
